text: (sigh) Adam Sandler, .....by having grown-up humor, you make it more CHILDISH. By modernizing the dialogue, you make it more DATED. And by changing the source material, you show how much you DON'T respect what's already perfect. I'm not going to act like everything video game creators wrote was a masterpiece, but when they got it right, they got it right. They don't NEED to be updated. They don't NEED to be fixed. They don't even really need to have MOVIES made about them! But if you're GOING to do it, the very least you can do is understand the source material. They're NOT just simple kids games. They're games that we are continuing to play even today. They're games that we remember years later, even when other games fade from our memory. They're games we will never forget - and for good reason! They're games that helped shape our childhoods, through well thought-out writing, imaginative drawings and endearing morals. And the idea of this... PIXELS... shaping somebody's childhood, the fact that it even has the same name... just makes me sick to my stomach! Maybe these "simple kids games" are far more adult than you give them credit for. And I guarantee that'll show, when years later, both children and adults will still be playing these "simple kids games" while pandering bullshit like this disappears out of people's consciousness - also for good reason! Good art doesn't come from focus groups and statistics. It comes from people who share how they see things in their own unique way.

text: Tbh, this looks like it's not gonma be that good. :/  Wreck-It Ralph did it right, where 90% of the movie was in arcades with characters to match. Hell, it even brought in modern ones! And it worked because of the setting! This taking place nonexclusively in arcades, you'd expect some more popular, modern video game characters to be in it. People like Mario, Sonic, Kirby, Ratchet & Clank (upcoming movie advertisement), Nathan Drake, Master Chief, even a GTA character could work, if developed into it right. THE ENTIRE SMASH BROS. ROSTER could even be thrown in!!! (though the closest we'll probably get is the hammer) That's what this movie could use.  The whole Iwatani, creator of Pac-Man thing is one thing they did right, and I believe they should expand on it. But cliche stuff like bringing a potential hero out of jail, and... *Adam Sandler,* is some of the fixed stuff about it.  Don't get me wrong, this movie could be good, but it's chances are slim. Adam Sandler isn't really known for good movies anymore....

text: Hehe... when I think about old video games I think of Pac-Man & Mario & Donkey King, yes of course. But I also think of all those computer games that MECC & The Learning Company made available to schools across the country (my mom was a teacher and my fellow teacher's kids friends and I spent a lot of time in the computer lab after school waiting for our parents to get done with meetings). Oregon Trail (original & Deluxe), Yukon Trail, Amazon Trail (all the Trails, really). Where In The World Is Carmen Sandiego? Crystal Quest. Storybook Weaver (though we all outgrew that one pretty quickly).   That said, when I saw this trailer my first idea was of ladies dropping like flies all over Portland & then the explanation being, "Well, their names were either Sarah or Beth... and Sarah and Beth are the ones that always die of cholera or exhaustion on Oregon Trail..."   Sigh. So glad most of these games can be found via flash online.  Might just grab the laptop and play some Oregon Trail Deluxe before I get back to class (I'm the teacher now...) :-) :-) :-)

text: I just got back from Pixels. What I can tell you is this: It's not good, but I didn't hate it like everyone else did. From what I've heard from every review I've read, they were pretty harsh on it.  I'd say the positives are visual effects and when the video games are attacking.  Everyone in their reviews have immaturely disregard the action sequences and the visual effects due to them being in an Adam Sandler movie. Plus there are cool cameos by a lot of 80's property.  But the negatives are it's still an Adam Sandler movie with jokes that don't work and it doesn't know what it want to be. There are times where it's tries to have kid friend moment, but then it turns into a adult joke.  I'd say your better off renting it at RedBox and skip to the action scenes.   So yeah, it's a rental.  It wasn't good, I wasn't mad like everyone else did.

text: As an honest movie goer and not some paid-to-critique critic, I thought this movie was great! It used the video game concept nicely and the CGI is fantastic! Extra props for being able to make a movie out of a short 3 minute film. And finally, like them or not, you can't deny that Adam Sandler and Kevin James are at least decent actors. The only issues I had were that the beginning felt rushed (which is fine, why make us wait for the action) and Q*Bert's voice. Overall, I strongly suggest you go see it your self. Don't be a blind critic follower. Even my non-gamer parents thought it was entertaining and they enjoyed all the 80's movie/TV show/video game references. It also does have its good one-liners. Go see it. It's one of those movies where the only your opinion is the most trusted.

text: I just got back from Pixels. What I can tell you is this: It's not good, but I didn't hate it like everyone else did. From what I've heard from every review I've read, they were pretty harsh on it.  I'd say the positives are visual effects and when the video games are attacking. Everyone in their reviews have immaturely disregard the action sequences and the visual effects due to them being in an Adam Sandler movie. Plus there are cool cameos by a lot of 80's property.  But the negatives are it's still an Adam Sandler movie with jokes that don't work and it doesn't know what it want to be. There are times where it's tries to have kid friend moment, but then it turns into a adult joke. I'd say your better off renting it at RedBox and skip to the action scenes. So yeah, it's a rental.  It wasn't good, I wasn't mad like everyone else did.

text: I went to see the movie today and I personally enjoyed it, but mostly due to the nostalgia. Honestly, the main reason your watching it is to see Q*bert, Pac-Man, Donkey Kong, Centipede etc. on the silver screen (that and seeing Peter Dinklage rocking a badass mullet and a bloody sci-fi cannon/minigun thing). The action scenes are amazing and the pixelated video game look really make these scenes feel more fresh and original than they ultimately are. The comedy does make you giggle at points but ultimately it's the same old meh stuff you come to expect in a movie starring Sandler.   Overall, Pixels was a decent enough film which didn't lack originality or fun, but did lack a decent script, and this certainly shows more in certain areas. I rate pixels a 5.9 out of 10. It isn't a bad film and it had a great director and mostly decent cast, but I feel that in the hands of a better writer with slightly altered cast this film could have been so much more.  As it stands it is enjoyable but feels like a bit of a wasted opportunity. But that's just my opinion.
